---

There's an annoying philistinism in some areas of mathematics,
including my own area of geometric group theory,
of pooh-poohing category theory.

It's easy to see why:
if you browse the [nLab](https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/HomePage) or the [Stacks project](https://stacks.math.columbia.edu/) or talk to a PL theory person who knows too much Haskell,
you mostly get what sounds like meaningless gobbledigook—excuse me, I meant _abstract nonsense._
This isn't to bash the work that went into these projects, which are valuable references once you learn how to read them.
The problem is that many people don't discover why they might want to.

Ostensibly, the aim of a field like geometric group theory, low-dimensional topology or analysis,
is concerned with answering concrete questions about fairly specific objects.
Such and such family of solitons, or Artin groups or knots, or what have you.
Often a strong geometric intuition or a willingness to get one's hands dirty with the simplest nontrivial example
is a key part of the work.
Knowledge of category theory often does not help here.
Knowing that an HNN extension is an example of a _co-inserter_
is very different from being able to comfortably work with its Bass–Serre tree.
Everyone in mathematics has met an approximation of the bright senior undergrad or first-year grad student
who appears to have swallowed _Category Theory for the Working Mathematician_ whole.
This student might use abstract nonsense as a deflection, a way of avoiding actually getting their hands dirty learning a field.

That being said, there really is a time for theory-building,
and geometric group theory for the most part falls on its face at this step.
It's great for definitions to be difficult so that theorems can be easy,
for instance, but [some definitions are still too difficult.](https://arxiv.org/pdf/2601.15410)
To me, this signals a lack of time spent trying to fit tools into a bigger picture.

Anyway, that's enough polemics from me for today.
The purpose of this post is to introduce a concept familiar to folks working in category theory
that suffers from a lack of attention from group theorists:
the notion of a _subgroupoid_ of a group.
In an effort to make it relevant to a geometric group theorist,
I'll close by reformulating the definitions of _height_ and _width_ of subgroups
as properties of a subgroupoid.

# Background

I'm going to _fly_ through this because you probably have seen this stuff before,
and if you haven't, you should do more work understanding it than this post is gonna provide.

A _groupoid_ is a small category where every arrow is invertible.

If that's too fast for you, you have two sets [`V \mathsf{G}`]($mathtex) of _objects_ and [`E \mathsf{G}`]($mathtex) of _arrows._
I'll use function notation for arrows: [`f\colon x \to y`]($mathtex) saying that [`f \in E \mathsf{G}`]($mathtex) is an arrow
with _source object_ [`\iota(f) = x \in V\mathsf{G}`]($mathtex) and _target_ object [`\tau(f) = y \in V\mathsf{G}`]($mathtex).
Arrows [`f\colon x \to y`]($mathtex) and [`g \colon y \to z`]($mathtex)
can compose like functions as [`g \circ f = g f \colon x \to z`]($mathtex),
and each object [`x`]($mathtex) has an identity arrow [`1_x \colon x \to x`]($mathtex).
Composition is associative and identity arrows are (two-sided) identities for composition.
Finally if [`f\colon x \to y`]($mathtex) is an arrow, there is an arrow [`f^{-1}\colon y \to x`]($mathtex)
such that [`f \circ f^{-1} = 1_y`]($mathtex) and [`f^{-1} \circ f = 1_x`]($mathtex).

You might have heard "a group is a groupoid with one object."
This is true: if [`G`]($mathtex) is a group, let [`G`]($mathtex) itself denote the object
and each element [`g \in G`]($mathtex) becomes an arrow [`g \colon G \to G`]($mathtex).
Composition is the group operation and inversion is inversion.

Morphisms of groupoids are _functors:_ [`F \colon \mathsf{H} \to \mathsf{G}`]($mathtex)
sends, for example [`f \colon x \to y`]($mathtex) in [`\mathsf{H}`]($mathtex) to [`F f \colon F x \to F y`]($mathtex) in [`\mathsf{G}`]($mathtex),
so there are assignments of objects to objects and arrows to arrows.
Composition and identities must be respected.

A _natural transformation,_ _natural isomorphism,_
or my emerging favorite terminology, a _conjugacy_ [`\eta`]($mathtex)
between functors [`F, K \colon \mathsf{H} \to \mathsf{G}`]($mathtex)
is an assignment, for each object [`x \in V \mathsf{H}`]($mathtex), of an _arrow_ [`\eta_x \colon F x \to K x`]($mathtex)
in [`\mathsf{G}`]($mathtex) such that for each arrow [`f \colon x \to y`]($mathtex) in [`\mathsf{H}`]($mathtex),
the equation
```=mathtex
K f \circ \eta_x = \eta_y \circ F f
```
is true in [`\mathsf{G}`]($mathtex).
The notation is [`\eta \colon F \Rightarrow K`]($mathtex).

I like the word conjugacy because in the case where [`H`]($mathtex) and [`G`]($mathtex) are groups,
a functor is a homomorphism and a conjugacy is simply a choice of an element [`\eta \in G`]($mathtex)
with the property that [`K(h) = \eta F(h) \eta^{-1}`]($mathtex) for all elements [`h \in H`]($mathtex).

An _equivalence_ of groupoids [`\mathsf{G}`]($mathtex) and [`\mathsf{H}`]($mathtex) is a pair of functors 
[`F \colon \mathsf{G} \to \mathsf{H}`]($mathtex) and [`K \colon \mathsf{H} \to \mathsf{G}`]($mathtex)
and conjugacies [`\eta \colon 1_{\mathsf{G}} \Rightarrow K F`]($mathtex) and [`\epsilon \colon F K \Rightarrow 1_{\mathsf{H}}`]($mathtex).

Assuming the Axiom of Choice,
a functor [`F`]($mathtex) is an equivalence if and only if it is _full_ (surjective on arrows [`Fx \to Fy`]($mathtex)),
_faithful_ (injective on arrows [`x \to y`]($mathtex)) and _essentially surjective_ 
(every object [`y`]($mathtex) in the target groupoid is connected to an object [`Fx`]($mathtex) by an arrow [`Fx \to y`]($mathtex)).

# Group Systems are Groupoids

A groupoid is _connected_ if between every pair of objects [`x`]($mathtex) and [`y`]($mathtex), there is an arrow [`x \to y`]($mathtex).
A groupoid is _contractible_ if it is connected and the aforementioned arrow is _unique._
Every nonempty connected groupoid [`\mathsf{H}`]($mathtex) is equivalent to the group [`\mathsf{H}(v,v)`]($mathtex)
of arrows [`v \to v`]($mathtex) for some (and hence any) object [`v \in V\mathsf{H}`]($mathtex).
A nonempty contractible groupoid is equivalent to the trivial group.

If [`v \in V\mathsf{G}`]($mathtex) is an object, its _connected component_ is the set of objects [`w`]($mathtex) in [`\mathsf{G}`]($mathtex)
such that there is an arrow [`v \to w`]($mathtex).
Suppose [`\{ [v_i] : i \in I \}`]($mathtex) is the set of connected components of [`\mathsf{G}`]($mathtex).
We can construct a _spanning groupoid_ from this set
by choosing for each [`w \in [v_i]`]($mathtex) a unique arrow [`s_w \colon v_i \to w`]($mathtex),
with the stipulation that the arrow [`s_{v_i} \colon v_i \to v_i`]($mathtex) is [`1_{v_i}`]($mathtex).
Completing this by addding in identities and compositions, we get a contractible groupoid [`\mathsf{S}`]($mathtex)
with vertex set [`V\mathsf{G}`]($mathtex).
With all of this data, one can show that each arrow [`f \colon v \to w`]($mathtex) factors uniquely as
[`f = s_w f_i s_v^{-1}`]($mathtex), where [`s_v \colon v_i \to v`]($mathtex) and [`s_w \colon v_i \to w`]($mathtex) are in [`\mathsf{S}`]($mathtex)
and [`f_i \colon v_i \to v_i`]($mathtex) is an element of the group [`G_i = \mathsf{G}(v_i, v_i)`]($mathtex).

Every groupoid, then, is equivalent to what [J.P. Mutanguha](https://mutanguha.com) denotes
a _group system:_ an indexed disjoint union of groups.
Explicitly, if [`\{ [v_i] : i \in I \}`]($mathtex) is the set of connected components of [`\mathsf{G}`]($mathtex),
then [`\mathsf{G}`]($mathtex) is equivalent to the disjoint union of groups
[`\bigsqcup_{i \in I} G_i`]($mathtex), where [`G_i = \mathsf{G}(v_i,v_i)`]($mathtex).

# Subgroupoids of Groups

A _subgroupoid_ [`\mathsf{H}`]($mathtex) of a group [`G`]($mathtex)
is a groupoid [`\mathsf{H}`]($mathtex) together with a functor [`F \colon \mathsf{H} \to G`]($mathtex)
with _trivial kernel,_ meaning that if [`F f = 1_G`]($mathtex), then [`f`]($mathtex) is an identity arrow.

Let's analyze what this means.
By our discussion in the previous section,
we should consider the groups [`H_i = \mathsf{H}(v_i,v_i)`]($mathtex) where [`\{ [v_i] : i \in I \}`]($mathtex)
is the set of connected components of [`\mathsf{H}`]($mathtex).
On each such group [`F`]($mathtex) restricts to an _injective homomorphism,_
so each group [`H_i`]($mathtex) _is a subgroup_ of [`G`]($mathtex).
Each arrow [`s_v \colon v_i \to v`]($mathtex) maps to an _element_ [`g_v \in G`]($mathtex)
and the stipulation that no arrow (necessarily) of the form [`s_w h_i s_v^{-1}`]($mathtex) maps to the identity says that
if [`v`]($mathtex) and [`w`]($mathtex) are distinct elements of [`[v_i]`]($mathtex), the _cosets_ [`g_v H_i`]($mathtex) are distinct in [`G`]($mathtex).

A _connected_ subgroupoid [`\mathsf{H}`]($mathtex) of a group [`G`]($mathtex) 
therefore corresponds to a set of cosets of a given subgroup [`H \le G`]($mathtex).
The groupoid [`\mathsf{H}`]($mathtex) therefore has at most [`G / H`]($mathtex) many objects
I'll say that a component [`\mathsf{H}_i`]($mathtex) of a subgroupoid [`\mathsf{H}`]($mathtex) is _total_
if it has [`G / H_i`]($mathtex) for its set of objects,
and that [`\mathsf{H}`]($mathtex) is _total_ if each component is.
(I don't love "total". Maybe another name could be ["wide"](https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/wide+subcategory), which generally has a slightly different meaning; if you have a better name, please let me know.) 

# Height and Width 

Suppose [`G`]($mathtex) is a group.
Typically [`G`]($mathtex) should be finitely generated, perhaps even finitely presented,
but the following definition makes some amount of sense for a group [`G`]($mathtex).

First, we say the _height_ of an infinite subgroup [`H \le G`]($mathtex) is [`n`]($mathtex) if there exist distinct cosets [`\{ g_1H, \ldots, g_nH \}`]($mathtex) such that the intersection [`\bigcap_{i=1}^n g_iHg_i^{-1}`]($mathtex) is infinite and [`n`]($mathtex) is maximum possible.

Next, we say that the _width_ of an infinite subgroup [`H \le G`]($mathtex) is [`n`]($mathtex) if there are distinct cosets as above so that _pairwise_ we have that [`g_iHg_i^{-1} \cap g_jHg_j^{-1}`]($mathtex) and again [`n`]($mathtex) is maximum possible.

Finite width implies finite height.

This is phrased both simply and cleanly in the language of subgroupoids:
If [`\mathsf{H}`]($mathtex) is a total subgroupoid of [`G`]($mathtex),
the inclusion witnesses "vertex" or "isotropy" groups [`\mathsf{H}(v,v)`]($mathtex) as subgroups of [`G`]($mathtex).
A component [`\mathsf{H}_i`]($mathtex) of [`\mathsf{H}`]($mathtex) has _width_ (or respectively _height_) [`n`]($mathtex)
if [`H_i = \mathsf{H}(v_i,v_i)`]($mathtex) is infinite
and there is a collection of [`n`]($mathtex) objects in [`\mathsf{H}_i`]($mathtex) 
(which are, remember, subgroups of [`G`]($mathtex) conjugate to [`H_i`]($mathtex) by conjugators from distinct cosets)
with pairwise (or respectively total) infinite intersection
and [`n`]($mathtex) is chosen maximum possible.
A subgroupoid [`\mathsf{H}`]($mathtex) therefore has width (or height) [`n`]($mathtex)
if [`n`]($mathtex) is the maximum width (or height) among its components.
